<br>
OOC - I have just had the pleasure of meeting some of the family tonight and now I'm browsing and find this!  This is an excellent idea.  I grouped with Lemeth and Antoin in Highpass ramp area of the Karanas.  What great roleplayers- but not too overdone. In any case here's my story so far(IC):<br>
<br>
All of my life, I can remember one thing:  Fishing.  I think I was fishing before I could walk.  My father and I would sit on the shore, underneath the shroud of Toxxulia, all day, everyday.<br>
<br>
We were not rich.  He could not afford to send me to one of the Arcane schools.  My lessons were taught to me in the sand with sticks- and washed away with the tide.  Eventually he worked out a deal to supply the Deepwater Knights with some of our catch and have me tutored in the ways of the Oceanlord.  &quot;For all that is good in our life, we owe him,&quot;  he would say.<br>
<br>
I don't remember my mother.  However, I remember how father would have business &quot;meetings&quot; with his brother-in-law, Jharud.  Jharud was from Paineel.  I don't remember why they met but I know they argued a lot.<br>
<br>
The last time I saw my father, we were standing on a small dock.  I had brought my pole to fish, but there was an evil looking man there, and I noticed too late that father had not brought any gear, but wore a sword.  My father got in a small boat to cross the water.  Jharud, it seems, had stirred up trouble with the Kerrans.  Since my father was friendly with them, he was going to work something out.   As my father's smiling face faded into the mist, the evil looking man began chanting.<br>
<br>
I knew little of the art of necromancy then.  All I know is that when I try to remember my father's face, fading into the distant darkness, I see the face of the hideous creature that stood before me.  Instead of the kind hopeful eyes promising me that he would return, I see empty sockets of death.<br>
<br>
I dropped my fishing pole, my only worldly possession, and ran.  I did not stop for the emissary who passed me.  I did not stop for the wandering kobolds (who did not bother me, because we never bothered them), and  I did not stop when the guards called my name.  <br>
<br>
I spent that long, cold night huddled in a dark corner behind a bookshelf on the highest floor of our great Library (a place I'd never been before- except on errands).  I was waiting for my father to return.<br>
<br>
Somehow, I knew he wouldn't.<br>
<br>
OOC- sounds like I could fit the role of a second cousin or something.  In any case I'll look you all up in game.<br>
<br>
Hueth<br>
